30. Your project uses version 5.60.0 of the hashicorp/aws provider, locked in the .terraform.lock.hcl file. A new version 5.65.0 has been released that you need.
Your version constraint is ~> 5.0. What must you run to upgrade?
terraform init -upgrade 
The dependency lock file (.terraform.lock.hcl) pins the exact provider versions resolved during the last terraform init. Running terraform init without flags respects the 
lock file and continues using the pinned version, even if newer compatible versions exist. The -upgrade flag tells Terraform to ignore the lock file selections, check for the 
newest versions that satisfy your version constraints, download them, and update the lock file accordingly. Deleting the lock file manually is not recommended because it 
removes the checksum verification that protects against supply chain attacks.

31. Your organization has a shared VPC that was created manually in the AWS console six months ago. You now want to manage this VPC with Terraform without recreating it. 
What's the correct approach?
The "import" block is specifically designed for bringing existing infrastructure that was created outside of Terraform under Terraform management. The workflow starts by 
writing a resource block in your Terraform configuration that matches the existing infrastructure, then adding an import block that maps your resource address to the actual
resource ID in your cloud provider. When you run terraform plan, Terraform associates your resource definition with the existing infrastructure and shows any configuration 
differences. After running terraform apply, the resource is fully managed by Terraform without having been destroyed or recreated.

