40. A colleague is confused because a sensitive output value still appears when they run terraform output db_connection_string directly even though sensitive = true is set.
What should you explain? Setting sensitive = true on an output encrypts the value in the state file using AES-256 encryption, but the terraform output command decrypts it automatically
The sensitive argument on output blocks controls display redaction, not access control. When set to true, Terraform replaces the value with (sensitive value) in plan and apply
CLI output. However, the terraform output command is explicitly designed to retrieve output values, so it displays the value even when marked sensitive. Importantly,
sensitive = true does not encrypt the value in the state file — sensitive values are stored in plaintext in state, which is why securing the state file itself remains critical.

41. You manage 15 workspaces that all deploy to the same AWS account. What steps should you take to simplify credential management when they rotate? (select two)
HCP Terraform projects let you organize related workspaces into logical groups, and variable sets let you define reusable collections of variables that can be applied at
different scopes. By grouping your workspaces into a project and then creating a project-scoped variable set containing your AWS credentials, every workspace in that project
automatically inherits those values. When credentials need to rotate, you update them in one place — the variable set — and the change propagates to all workspaces in the project.

42. How does Terraform's resource graph affect infrastructure operations? (select three)
Terraform builds a dependency graph to determine execution order by analyzing references between resources, creating implicit dependencies automatically. Non-dependent resources
are processed in parallel, with a default limit of 10 concurrent operations, significantly speeding up infrastructure deployment. When implicit dependencies aren't sufficient,
you can use the depends_on argument to explicitly define dependencies. The graph is built in memory during plan and apply operations based on your current configuration — not
on file order — and it is not saved to disk.

